Colombia has secured total borrowingsthis year for 1.95 billion dlrs, of which 1.40 billioncorrespond to loans arranged before 1986, Director of PublicCredit Mauricio Cabrera said.    Cabrera said about half of the borrowings would come fromthe World Bank and the Inter-American Development Bank.    He was speaking at a forum for industrialists upon hisreturn from London where he attended the signing of a 50 mlndlr floating rate note, Colombia's first such offering on theeuromarket.    Cabrera reaffirmed that Colombia has no intention ofrescheduling  its foreign debt, which he put at 14.35 billiondlrs, of which 11.35 billion are from the public sector.    For the international banking community, Colombia continuesto be "the best house in spite of being in the worstneighbourhood," he said.    He said debt servicing will remain a burden in 1987 andwill amount to 34.6 pct of total exports. REUTER&#3;